[[[ TITLE ]]]
Capacity Region of a Class of Deterministic K -Receiver Broadcast Channels with Degraded Message Sets
[[[ AUTHORS ]]]
Hon Fah Chong
Ying-Chang Liang
[[[ ABSTR ]]]
Abstract—In this paper, we establish the capacity region of a new class of deterministic K-receiver broadcast channels with degraded message sets, where the output Y i , i ∈ {1, . . . , K}, is a deterministic function of the channel input X and user i requires messages (M 1 , . . . , M i ). In this class of deterministic broadcast channels, the outputs Y 1 → Y 2 → Y 3 . . . → Y K form a Markov chain for a sufﬁcient class of input probability distributions p (x) ∈ P. The main idea of the coding strategy is to allow user i to decode not only its own messages (M 1 , . . . , M i ), but also part of the messages (M i+1 , . . . , M K ) intended for user j ∈ {i + 1, i + 2, . . . , K}. We then show that the achievable rate region attains the capacity region of this new class of deterministic K-receiver broadcast channels.
[[[ BODY ]]]
A K-receiver broadcast channel (BC) with degraded mes- sage sets, (M 1 , . . . , M K ), where user i ∈ {1, . . . , K} requires messages (M 1 , . . . , M i ) is shown in Fig. 1. User 1 is only able to decode the lowest quality version M 1 , user 2 is able to decode the next higher quality version (M 1 , M 2 ), and so on. Such a conﬁguration may correspond to the situation where content e.g., video or music, is being broadcast with different levels of quality.
Korner and Marton [1] established the capacity region of the the two-receiver BC with degraded message sets, (M 1 , M 2 ), where M 1 is the common message intended for both users and M 2 is the private message intended only for user 2. It was later conjectured [2, Conj. 5] that a straightforward extension of the Korner-Marton region to the three-receiver multilevel BC would be optimal. In this channel, the output of receiver 2 is a degraded version of the output of receiver 1; there are two messages, (M 1 , M 2 ), where M 1 is the common message intended for all three users and M 2 is the private message intended for only user 1. However, Nair and El Gamal [3] showed that a straightforward extension of the Korner-Marton region was strictly suboptimal and that the capacity region could be attained by allowing user 3 to decode part of the message M 2 intended for user 1. Later on, Chong and Liang [4] established the capacity region for the Gaussian MIMO three-receiver multilevel BC.
In a similar line of research, Prabhakaran et al. considered the K-receiver MIMO linear deterministic BC with degraded message sets [5]. They established the complete solution
for the three-user case. For the general K-user case, they characterized the solution for two cases: (i) where there is one common message M 1 and another private message M K for user K (i.e., M 2 = . . . = M K−1 = ∅) and (ii) where there is one common message M 1 and another message M 2 to be de- coded by all users except user 1 (i.e., M 3 = . . . = M K = ∅). In [6], Saeedi et al. extended the result to the case where there is one common message M 1 and another message M 3 to be decoded by all users except for users 1 and 2 (i.e., M 2 = M 4 = M 5 . . . = M K = ∅). An important ingredient used was to allow the users who decode only the common message to decode part of the message M 3 as well. However, the complete characterization of the capacity region of general linear deterministic BCs with degraded message sets remains unresolved.
In [3, Thm. 2], Nair and El Gamal established an achievable rate region for the general three-receiver BC with three- degraded message sets. However, an extension to an arbitrary K-receiver case seems difﬁcult.
In this paper, we make use of a simpler coding strategy that allows us to establish a compact description of an achievable rate region for the general K-receiver case. We make use of the same ideas in [3] and [6] by allowing user i to decode part of the messages (M i+1 , . . . , M K ) not intended for itself. Finally, we show that our coding strategy attains the capacity region of a new class of deterministic BC, the essentially degraded deterministic BC.
In Section II, we ﬁrst provide some formal deﬁnitions of the general K-receiver BC with degraded message sets as well
as the essentially degraded deterministic K-receiver BC. In Section III, we determine an achievable rate region for the general K-receiver BC with degraded message sets. In Section IV, we establish the capacity region of the essentially degraded deterministic K-receiver BC with degraded message sets. We also consider a speciﬁc linear deterministic BC to show that this is indeed a new class of BCs for which the capacity region was formerly unknown.
